@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place 'Thumper' where you want
on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or
Libraries are needed. The only requirement is that your Workbench must
have at least 8 colours.

                             How to play?

  To play, click on an empty space, indicated by a small square, next
to the shape you want to move, this will push, or 'Thump' that shape
and unless there is wall or another shape in the way, it will move one
space from the position you clicked on, as shown in the following
illustration:

  . . . .      . o . .
  . o . .      . . . .    ...Where "." = empty space
  . * o .  ->  . * . o             "o" = shape to move
  . o . .      . . . .             "*" = clicked space
  . . . .      . o . .

  ...Note that clicking on a wall will have no effect, and besides,
it would be too easy ;)

  The corresponding 'receiving' shapes are like the shapes to be
moved, but with the black and white edges reversed, when a shape is
placed on a receiving shape, it cannot be moved again... and no other
shape, even those of the same pattern, can go there. Note that a
receiving shape, when empty, can act as an empty tile to move shapes,
but not when a shape has been put on such a tile... so beware!

  On some game boards, several shapes of the same pattern may be
present, and the corresponding receiving shapes are obviously of the
same number. You are on your own as to decide which shape goes where.

  If you get stuck, you can replay a game board anytime by clicking on
the '@{b}Replay@{ub}' button. Note, however, that everytime you replay a game
board, the current number of moves made on that board will accumulate
until the board is completed.

  Have fun!


NOTE: If you have game board ideas, please @{"send them to me" link mrware}, I'll add
them on a future version of the game. One thing to keep in mind is
that to be useable for this game, the boards must not exceed an area
of 15 by 15 spaces (including outside walls), and up to 5 type of
shapes along with their own 'receiving' shapes can be used for a
game board... thanks!

@endnode

